# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloudflare-kv
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded in 2009 by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The company went public on the New York Stock Exchange in 2019 under the ticker symbol NET.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare has since expanded its offerings to include edge computing through its Workers platform, a public DNS resolver (1.1.1.1), and a VPN-like service known as WARP.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In recent years, the company has integrated artificial intelligence into its infrastructure, acquiring companies such as Replicate and launching tools to manage AI bots and scrapers.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] According to W3Techs, Cloudflare is used by approximately 21.3% of all websites on the Internet as of January 2026.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The company has been the subject of controversy regarding its policy of content neutrality.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare has also faced criticism and litigation regarding copyright infringement by websites using its services, notably losing a lawsuit against Japanese publishers in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The company experienced significant global outages in late 2025 which disrupted services for major platforms internationally.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded on July 26, 2009, by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Prince and Holloway had previously collaborated on Project Honey Pot, a product of Unspam Technologies that partly inspired the basis of Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2009, the company was venture-capital funded.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] On August 15, 2019, Cloudflare submitted its S-1 filing for an initial public offering on the New York Stock Exchange under the stock ticker NET.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] It opened for public trading on September 13, 2019, at $15 per share.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare co-founder and COO Michelle Zatlyn was named president.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare has acquired web-services and security companies, including StopTheHacker (February 2014), CryptoSeal (June 2014), Eager Platform Co.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Replicate (November 2025), and Human Native (January 2026).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Since at least 2017, Cloudflare has used a wall of lava lamps at its San Francisco headquarters as a source of randomness for encryption keys, alongside double pendulums at its London offices and a Geiger counter at its Singapore offices.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The lava lamp installation implements the Lavarand method, where a camera transforms the unpredictable shapes of the "lava" blobs into a digital image.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In Q4 2022, Cloudflare provided paid services to 162,086 customers.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In October 2024, Cloudflare won a lawsuit against patent troll Sable Networks.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Sable paid Cloudflare $225,000, granted it a royalty-free license to its patent portfolio, and dedicated its patents to the public by abandoning its patent rights.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In November 2025, it was announced Cloudflare had agreed to acquire Replicate, a San Francisco–based platform that enables software developers to run, fine-tune, and deploy open-source machine-learning models via an API without managing infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare released an analysis regarding BGP routing leaks observed from the Venezuelan state-owned ISP CANTV (AS8048), which occurred on January 2 coincides with the arrest of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] While some security researchers had speculated that the outages were linked to U.S. cyber operations, Cloudflare's data indicated that the anomalies were consistent with a pattern of "insufficient routing export and import policies" by the ISP rather than malicious external interference.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare acquired Human Native, an AI data marketplace that brokers transactions between developers and content creators, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] On January 16, 2026, Cloudflare acquired The Astro Technology Company, the developers behind the open-source web framework Astro.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In May 2026, Cloudflare announced the elimination of approximately 1,100 positions, around 20 percent of its workforce, in a restructuring the company attributed to the rapid adoption of artificial intelligence tools.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The announcement coincided with the company's first-quarter 2026 earnings, which reported a record $639.8 million in quarterly revenue, a 34 percent year-over-year increase.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] CEO Matthew Prince stated the cuts were not driven by performance concerns but reflected roles made obsolete by AI, and that Cloudflare expected to employ more people by the end of 2027 than at any point during 2026.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides network and security products for consumers and businesses, utilizing edge computing, reverse proxies for web traffic, data center interconnects, and a content distribution network to serve content across its network of servers.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] It supports transport layer protocols TCP, UDP, QUIC, and many application layer protocols such as DNS over HTTPS, SMTP, and HTTP/2 with support for HTTP/2 Server Push.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] As of 2023, Cloudflare handles an average of 45 million HTTP requests per second.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] As of 2024, Cloudflare servers are powered by AMD EPYC 9684X processors.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare also provides analysis and reports on large-scale outages, including Verizon's October 2024 outage.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released an open-source CMS called EmDash, intended to align with serverless and edge-based architecture.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2023, Cloudflare launched "Workers AI", a framework allowing for use of Nvidia GPU's within Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare launched a tool that prevents bots from scraping websites.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] To build automatic bot detector models, the company analyzed "AI" bots and crawler traffic.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The company also launched an "AI" assistant to generate charts based on queries by leveraging "Workers AI".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced plans in September 2024 to launch a marketplace where website owners can sell "AI" model providers access to scrape their site's content.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In March 2025, Cloudflare announced a new feature called "AI Labyrinth", which combats unauthorized "AI" data scraping by serving fake "AI"-generated content to LLM bots.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In July, the company rolled out a permission-based setting to allow websites to automatically block online bots from scraping data and content.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare released AutoRAG into beta in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] AutoRAG (retrieval augmented generation) creates a vector database of a website's unstructured content to identify relationships between concepts.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] It is part of an initiative with Microsoft, alongside their NLWeb standard, to make websites easier for people and automated systems to query.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare and GoDaddy partnered in April 2026 to enable AI Crawl Control features on GoDaddy hosted websites.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] This would allow site owners to decide how AI bot crawlers interact with their content.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides free and paid DDoS mitigation services that protect customers from distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare received media attention in June 2011 for providing DDoS mitigation for the website of LulzSec, a black hat hacking group.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In March 2013, The Spamhaus Project was targeted by a DDoS attack that Cloudflare reported exceeded 300 gigabits per second (Gbit/s).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Patrick Gilmore, of Akamai, stated that at the time it was "the largest publicly announced DDoS attack in the history of the Internet".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] While trying to defend Spamhaus against the DDoS attacks, Cloudflare ended up being attacked as well; Google and other companies eventually came to Spamhaus' defense and helped it to absorb the unprecedented amount of attack traffic.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2014, Cloudflare began providing free DDoS mitigation for artists, activists, journalists, and human rights groups under the name "Project Galileo".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2017, it extended the service to electoral infrastructure and political campaigns under the name "Athenian Project".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] By 2025, more than 2,900 users and organizations were participating in Project Galileo, including 31 US states.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In February 2014, Cloudflare claimed to have mitigated an NTP reflection attack against an unnamed European customer, which it stated peaked at 400 Gbit/s.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In November 2014, it reported a 500 Gbit/s DDoS attack in Hong Kong.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In July 2021, the company claimed to have absorbed a DDoS attack three times larger than any it had previously recorded, which its corporate blog implied was over 1.2 Tbit/s in total.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In February 2023, Cloudflare reported blocking a 71 million request-per-second DDoS attack which "the company says was the largest HTTP DDoS attack on record".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare blocked the then largest publicly recorded DDoS attack in August 2025, with volumetric attacks peaking at 11.5 terabits per second (tbps).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] This was surpassed in December 2025 when an Aisuru botnet launched a 31.4 tbps attack, with a requests-per-second rate exceeding 200 million, against multiple companies in the telecommunications sector, a campaign Cloudflare dubbed "The Night Before Christmas".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released a system designed to let users implement their own custom DDoS mitigation logic, using protocols built on User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2017, Cloudflare launched Cloudflare Workers, a serverless computing platform for creating new applications, augmenting existing ones, without configuring or maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] It has expanded to include Workers KV, a low-latency key-value data store; Cron Triggers, for scheduling Cron jobs; and additional tooling for developers to deploy and scale their code across the globe.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare released a JAMstack platform for developers to deploy websites on Cloudflare's Edge infrastructure, under the name "Pages".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2022, Cloudflare announced an Edge SQL database, D1, which is built on SQLite.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare and IBM announced a partnership providing bot management capabilities to protect IBM Cloud customers from malicious bots and automated threats.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The same month, Cloudflare was hired by SpaceX to boost the performance of Starlink.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In September, the company launched Cloudflare Fonts as a competitor to Google Fonts.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In April 2020, Cloudflare announced it was moving away from using reCAPTCHA in favor of hCaptcha.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In September 2022, Cloudflare began to test Turnstile – an alternative to CAPTCHA.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The product, instead of presenting a visual CAPTCHA for the user to solve, automatizes the verification process by conducting JavaScript-based checks inside the browser to determine whether the user is a real person or an automated entity.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The algorithm reportedly uses machine learning to optimize the process.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Through a contract with the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, Cloudflare provides registry and authoritative DNS services to the .gov top-level domain.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare also launched Cloudflare for Campaigns in 2020, to offer free cybersecurity tools to political campaigns.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Those tools expanded to include secure email systems in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In November 2020, Cloudflare announced Cloudflare for Teams, consisting of a DNS resolver and web gateway called "Gateway", and a zero-trust authentication service called "Access".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare released an Oblivious HTTP relay service in 2022, called Privacy Gateway.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced a partnership with PhonePe in January 2023 to secure its mobile payment system.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In February, Cloudflare launched Wildebeest to allow Mastodon users to set up and run their own instances on Cloudflare's infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare started the Project Cybersafe Schools program as part of a $20 million grant program from Amazon Web Services, making 70 percent of public school districts in the United States eligible for no-cost cybersecurity services.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In March 2024, it announced Firewall for AI to defend applications running large language models (LLMs).
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In September, Cloudflare announced Ephemeral IDs, which identifies fraudulent activity by linking behavior to a client through a short-lived, generated ID, rather than the traditional means of using an IP address.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The same month, the company also announced all ISP and equipment manufacturers could use its DNS resolvers for free.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare introduced the Cloudforce One threat events platform in March 2025, offering real-time insights into cyberattacks using data gathered from Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare's overarching secure access service edge (SASE) platform debuted in October 2020.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced the acquisition of Area 1 Security in February 2022, a company who developed a product designed to combat phishing email attacks.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare acquired Nefeli Networks in March 2024, a cloud networking company, co-founded by computer scientist Sylvia Ratnasamy.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare released a VPN-like service called WARP, and open sourced the custom underlying WireGuard implementation written in Rust.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In January 2021, the company began providing its "Waiting Room" digital queue product for free for COVID-19 vaccination scheduling under the title "Project Fair Shot".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Project Fair Shot later won a Webby People's Choice Award in 2022 for Event Management under the Apps & Software category.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In March 2023, Cloudflare announced post-quantum cryptography will be made freely and forever available to cloud services, applications and Internet connections.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare released the Speed Brain and Instant Purge features in September 2024, to significantly reduce page load latency by prefetching content, and invalidating cached content in under 150ms.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare announced plans to launch a new payment method, called Stripe Link, which went into beta in the fall.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Since 2010, Cloudflare has collaborated with the National Center for Missing & Exploited Children to provide data, files, and supplemental investigation from abuse reports observed on its network.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare designed a new NCMEC reporting system in 2024, updating it in 2025 by integrating Cloudflare Workflows and making the CSAM scanning tool accessible globally.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] On June 1, 2012, the hacker group UGNazi compromised some of Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince's accounts and redirected visitors of the website 4chan to a Twitter account belonging to UGNazi.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] They allegedly used social engineering to trick AT&T support staff into giving them access to Prince's voicemail, then exploited a vulnerability in Cloudflare's use of Google's two-factor authentication system.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Once in control of Prince's email account, UGNazi was able to redirect the 4chan domain through Cloudflare's database.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] From September 2016 until February 2017, a Cloudflare bug nicknamed Cloudbleed leaked sensitive data, including passwords and authentication tokens, from customer websites by sending extra data in response to web requests.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] On November 18, 2025, Cloudflare suffered a major global outage that caused widespread 500 errors, slowing down many platforms, making them unreachable or completely down for users around the world.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Access to WARP, Cloudflare's VPN service, was also briefly disabled in London.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] During the outage, a spokesperson for Cloudflare said the company had seen a "spike in unusual traffic", causing some traffic passing through its network to experience errors.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] At 14:23 UTC, *The Guardian* reported that Cloudflare had released a fix.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] It also reported that maintenance was due at various locations, though this is not known to have caused the outages.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] At 14:42 UTC, Cloudflare informed users on its status page that the fix had been implemented and that it would take some time for remaining post-deployment issues to be fixed.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] A technical postmortem of the incident was released the day following the outage.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare attributed the outage to a change in the configuration of a database, which caused an invalid file to be sent to all servers on the network.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] On December 5, Cloudflare suffered another global outage, which began at 09:00 AM UTC.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] This was the second such outage in three weeks to affect Cloudflare's services.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In January 2026, security researchers disclosed a vulnerability in Cloudflare's Web application firewall (WAF) that allowed attackers to bypass security rules and access origin servers directly.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The flaw existed in the handling of ACME challenge requests; the logic disabled WAF protections for requests targeting the `/.well-known/acme-challenge/` path without sufficiently verifying if the token matched an active validation attempt.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare patched the vulnerability in October 2025, stating that the issue was a logic flaw rather than a code execution vulnerability and that there was no evidence of exploitation.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare has established a content neutrality policy and opposes the policing of its customers on the basis of free speech unless said customers break the law.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The company has faced criticism for not banning hate speech websites and websites allegedly connected to terrorism groups.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare has maintained that no law enforcement agency has asked the company to discontinue these services and it closely monitors its obligations under U.S. laws.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2022, a research paper by Stanford University found that Cloudflare was a prominent CDN provider, among several other providers, that are disproportionately responsible for serving misinformation websites.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare has come under pressure due to its services being utilized to access far-right content.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DNS routing and DDoS protection for the white supremacist and neo-Nazi website *The Daily Stormer*.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2017, after previously refusing to take any action against the website, Cloudflare stopped providing its services to *The Daily Stormer* after an announcement on the website asserted that Cloudflare executives were privately supporting its ideology.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] As a self-described "free speech absolutist", Prince claimed he did not want to repeat the decision, and sought out protections for the company should they be faced with a similar situation in the future.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Prince further addressed the dangers of large companies deciding what is allowed to stay online, a concern shared by a number of civil liberties groups and privacy experts.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, a US digital rights group, said that services such as Cloudflare should not be deciding what speech is acceptable and that illegal content should be handled through the legal system.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare was criticized for providing services to the far-right discussion and imageboard 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The message board has been linked to mass shootings in the United States and the Christchurch mosque shootings in New Zealand.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In addition, a number of news organizations including *The Washington Post* and *The Daily Dot* have reported on the existence of child pornography and child sexual abuse discussion boards.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] A Cloudflare representative said that the platform "does not host the referenced websites, cannot block websites, and is not in the business of hiding companies that host illegal content".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare did not terminate service to 8chan until public and legal pressure mounted in the wake of the 2019 El Paso shooting, in which the associated manifesto was published to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In an interview with *The Guardian* immediately after the shooting, CEO Matthew Prince defended Cloudflare's support of 8chan, saying that he had a "moral obligation" to keep 8chan online.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] On August 5, 2019, two days after Prince's interview with The Guardian, Cloudflare terminated service to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare explained that 8chan "have proven themselves to be lawless and that lawlessness has caused multiple tragic deaths.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DDoS mitigation and acted as a reverse proxy for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The site often engages in harassment and doxxing of targets and has been implicated in the suicides of at least three people.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Kiwi Farms also has a reputation for transphobic content, and its users have been accused of swatting vulnerable individuals.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Although Cloudflare was not the primary website host, it did perform critical services to keep Kiwi Farms on-line, both protecting the site from denial-of-service attacks and optimizing content delivery.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2022, a campaign was launched by transgender activist Clara Sorrenti, who has previously been targeted by the forum, to pressure Cloudflare into terminating service for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare responded by issuing a statement on its abuse policies and saying it didn't want to set precedent for speech on the internet with its "extraordinary" decision.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The company also released a blog post and likened its services to that of a public utility, emphasizing that it does not believe in shutting down security services based on content it finds objectionable.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] They acknowledged that while it might be more popular to remove sites that the Cloudflare team finds offensive, it stood by its decision not to do so.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The company also defended its decision by saying that it donated all earnings from anti-LGBTIQ+ sites to an organization that advocated for LGBTIQ+ rights.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] On September 3, 2022, Cloudflare blocked Kiwi Farms, citing urgent escalating rhetoric against targets of Kiwi Farms, stating that there is an "unprecedented emergency and immediate threat to human life".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Switter was a social media network for the sex worker community, built by Australia-based company Assembly Four on Mastodon's open-source software, before Cloudflare dropped Switter as a client and ceased services in April 2018, citing terms of service violations.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] This occurred shortly after the passage of FOSTA/SESTA, a set of bills criminalizing websites that facilitate or support sex trafficking in 2018.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] SESTA weakened protections for Internet infrastructure companies and was criticized on free speech grounds due to concerns about disproportionate impact and disruptions to the lives of sex workers.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare said the move was "related to our attempts to understand FOSTA, which is a very bad law and [sets] a very dangerous precedent".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Assembly Four said that "Given Cloudflare's previous stances of privacy and freedom, as well as fighting alongside the EFF, we had hoped they would take a stand against FOSTA/SESTA".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2015, testimony to the United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs, it was reported that two of the top three online chat forums and nearly forty other web sites belonging to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) were guarded by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been cited in reports by The Spamhaus Project, an international spam tracking organization, for the high numbers of cybercriminal botnet operations hosted by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] An October 2015 report found that Cloudflare provisioned 40% of the SSL certificates used by typosquatting phishing sites, which use deceptive domain names resembling those of banks and payment processors to compromise Internet users' banking and other transactions.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been criticized for having a conflict of interest by providing DDoS protection to both the operators and victims of "stresser" services.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2018, Cloudflare was identified by the European Union's Counterfeit and Piracy Watch List as a "notorious market" which engages in, facilitates, or benefits from counterfeiting and piracy.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The report noted that Cloudflare hides and anonymizes the operators of 40% of the world's pirate sites, and 62% of the 500 largest such sites, and "does not follow due diligence when opening accounts for websites to prevent illegal sites from using its services".
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2020, an Italian court ruled Cloudflare had to block current and future domain names and IP addresses of the pirate IPTV service "IPTV THE BEST" for infringing on Lega Serie A intellectual property.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] At the time, Cloudflare was already blocking 22 domain names in Italy.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Following the December 2024 court ruling, the Spanish LaLiga requested that telephone operators block Cloudflare's IP address ranges in February 2025.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare hosted websites that illegally broadcast soccer matches.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] As a result, the pirate platform DuckVision was shut down before the derby between Real Madrid and Atlético Madrid.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The platform had 200,000 users and was backed by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] The blocks affected major legitimate websites, including X, Vimeo, Steam, GitHub, and the Royal Spanish Academy.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince responded that the company decided to remain providing services to Russian people to counter Russia's attempts to raise a 'digital iron curtain'.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] Cloudflare's Project Galileo, launched in 2014, offers DDoS protection to NGOs for free.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2022, they extended free protection to Ukrainian government and telecoms.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] In 2022, Japanese publishers Shueisha, Kodansha, Shogakukan, and Kadokawa Shoten filed a copyright lawsuit against Cloudflare, alleging that the service was distributing data to manga piracy sites and sought an injunction and ¥460 million (US$4 million) in damages.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] On November 19, 2025, a judge ruled in favor of the publishers.
[src:cloudflare-kv/cloudflare] While the ruling recognized approximately ¥3.6 billion (US$24 million) in damages, Cloudflare was ordered to pay a total amount of ¥500 million (US$3.6 million), as the publishers claimed that Cloudflare was only partially responsible for the damages.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] A **distributed data store** is a computer network where information is stored on more than one node, often in a replicated fashion.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] It is usually specifically used to refer to either a distributed database where users store information on a *number of nodes*, or a computer network in which users store information on a *number of peer network nodes*.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] Distributed databases are usually non-relational databases that enable a quick access to data over a large number of nodes.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] Some distributed databases expose rich query abilities while others are limited to a key-value store semantics.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] Examples of limited distributed databases are Google's Bigtable, which is much more than a distributed file system or a peer-to-peer network, Amazon's Dynamo and Microsoft Azure Storage.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] As the ability of arbitrary querying is not as important as the availability, designers of distributed data stores have increased the latter at an expense of consistency.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] But the high-speed read/write access results in reduced consistency, as it is not possible to guarantee both consistency and availability on a partitioned network, as stated by the CAP theorem.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] In peer network data stores, the user can usually reciprocate and allow other users to use their computer as a storage node as well.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] Information may or may not be accessible to other users depending on the design of the network.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] Most peer-to-peer networks do not have distributed data stores in that the user's data is only available when their node is on the network.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] However, this distinction is somewhat blurred in a system such as BitTorrent, where it is possible for the originating node to go offline but the content to continue to be served.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] Still, this is only the case for individual files requested by the redistributors, as contrasted with networks such as Hyphanet, Winny, Share and Perfect Dark where any node may be storing any part of the files on the network.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] Distributed data stores typically use an error detection and correction technique.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] Some distributed data stores (such as Parchive over NNTP) use forward error correction techniques to recover the original file when parts of that file are damaged or unavailable.
[src:cloudflare-kv/distributed-data-store] Others try again to download that file from a different mirror.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:cloudflare-kv/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] Eventually-consistent services are often classified as providing BASE semantics (basically-available, soft-state, eventual consistency), in contrast to traditional ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability).
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] Eventual consistency faces criticism for adding complexity to distributed software applications.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] This complexity arises because eventual consistency provides only a liveness guarantee (ensuring reads eventually return the same value) without safety guarantees—allowing any intermediate value before convergence.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] Application developers find this challenging because it differs from single-threaded programming, where variables reliably return their assigned values immediately.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] With weak consistency guarantees, developers must carefully consider these limitations, as incorrect assumptions about consistency levels can lead to subtle bugs that only surface during network failures or high concurrency.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] In order to ensure replica convergence, a system must reconcile differences between multiple copies of distributed data.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] The most appropriate approach to reconciliation depends on the application.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] A widespread approach is "last writer wins".
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] Another is to invoke a user-specified conflict handler.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] Timestamps and vector clocks are often used to detect concurrency between updates.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] Some people use "first writer wins" in situations where "last writer wins" is unacceptable.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] Whereas eventual consistency is only a liveness guarantee (updates will be observed eventually), **strong eventual consistency** (SEC) adds the safety guarantee that any two nodes that have received the same (unordered) set of updates will be in the same state.
[src:cloudflare-kv/eventual-consistency] A common approach to ensure SEC is conflict-free replicated data types.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] A **key-value database**, or **key-value store**, is a data storage paradigm designed for storing, retrieving, and managing associative arrays, a data structure more commonly known today as a *dictionary*.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Dictionaries contain a collection of *objects*, or *records*, which in turn have many different *fields* within them.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] These records are stored and retrieved using a *key* that uniquely identifies the record, and is used to find the data within the database.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Key-value databases differ from the better known relational databases (RDB).
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] RDBs pre-define the data structure in the database as a series of tables containing fields with well-defined data types.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Exposing the data types to the database program allows it to apply various optimizations.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] In contrast, key-value systems treat the value as opaque to the database itself, and typically support only simple operations such as storing, retrieving, updating, and deleting a value by its key.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] This offers considerable flexibility and makes such systems well suited to low-latency, high-throughput workloads dominated by direct key lookups, but less suitable for applications that require complex queries or explicit relationships among records.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] A lack of standardization, limited transaction support, and relatively simple query interfaces long restricted many key-value systems to specialized uses, but the rapid move to cloud computing after 2010 helped drive renewed interest in them as part of the broader NoSQL movement.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Some graph databases, such as ArangoDB, are also key–value databases internally, adding the concept of relationships (*pointers*) between records as a first-class data type.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Key–value systems span a wide consistency spectrum, from eventually consistent designs to strongly consistent or serializable ones, and some allow the consistency level to be configured as part of the trade-off against latency and availability.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Renewed interest in key–value and other NoSQL systems was driven in part by the demands of big data, distributed, and cloud applications.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Their scalability and availability made them attractive for cloud data management, although limited transaction support, low-level query interfaces, and the lack of standardization remained obstacles to wider adoption.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Some maintain data in memory (RAM), while others employ solid-state drives or rotating disks.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Some key–value systems add additional structure to their keys.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] For example, Oracle NoSQL Database organizes records using composite keys with "major" and "minor" components, an arrangement that Oracle compares to a directory-path structure in a file system.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] More generally, however, key–value stores are defined by their use of unique keys associated with opaque values and by their emphasis on simple key-based operations.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Unix included *dbm* (database manager), a minimal database library written by Ken Thompson for managing associative arrays with a single key and hash-based access.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Later implementations and related libraries included sdbm, GNU dbm (gdbm), and Berkeley DB.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] A more recent example is RocksDB, a persistent key–value storage engine developed at Facebook and designed for large-scale applications.
[src:cloudflare-kv/key-value-database] Other examples include in-memory systems such as Memcached and Redis, and persistent systems such as Berkeley DB, Riak, and Voldemort.
